A 1989 court ruling in the case voided all VA benefit decisions it had made based on the agency's assertion that only the skin disease chloracne was linked to Agent Orange.
Congress has ordered a review every two years of links of various diseases to the use of chemicals in Vietnam.
The plaintiffs wanted the VA ordered to pay the benefits, but Henderson ruled that the agency should revisit the denied claims.
``Initially, we did not think the chemicals would have an impact on the second generation,'' Cau said.